ough the long modern period from the Renaissance to the present, drawing on the work of historians, political scientists, literary scholars and philosophers. The result is a distinctly new argument about the complex and often mystified entanglements between literature, civility and violence in the anglophone Atlantic sphere. What now are our expectations of civility and literature, separately and together? How do these long-familiar but residually imprecise concepts stand up to the demands of the modern world? Simpson's argument is that, despite and perhaps because of their imperfect conceptualization, both persist as important protocols for the critique of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCourtesy in literature. 0aLiterature and morals. 0aLiterature and society. 0aViolence in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aLiterature.  aaesthetics.  acivil society.  acivility.  aliterary theory.  apedagogy.  asubalternity.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2022 Englishz978311099370708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2022z9783110993684oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664860 cprintz978150363274540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363309440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633094/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099370-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Li